<DOC><DOCNO> AP880829-0186 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-88 2249EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Arrests     08-29 0261</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Philippines-Arrests,0269</SECOND><HEAD>Troops Seize Three Renegade Soldiers</HEAD><DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Troops raided hideouts in the Manilasuburb of Quezon City on Monday and arrested three renegadesoldiers believed linked to supporters of former PresidentFerdinand Marcos, the military said.   That brought to at least 12 the number of purported right-wingactivists seized in raids in Manila and elsewhere since Friday.   Brig. Gen. Rodolfo Biazon, commander of the National CapitalRegional Defense Command, said, however, that nine of the suspectswere released pending further investigation.   He called the raids ``pre-emptive strikes'' to prevent anothercoup attempt against President Corazon Aquino.   The military has been on full alert in the Manila area sinceSaturday for Mrs. Aquino's visit to Brunei. She left for BruneiMonday and is expected to return Wednesday.   Military officials said troops seized 10 automatic rifles andhundreds of rounds of ammunition in the raids Monday.   Biazon said those arrested were believed linked to renegadeBrig. Gen. Jose Marie Zumel, a Marcos supporter and formersuperintendent of the Philippine Military Academy who has beensought since a coup attempt in January 1987.   He did not give the names of the three men arrested.   Brig. Gen. Galileo Kintanar, the armed forces' chiefintelligence officer, told a congressional committee Monday thatrenegade soldiers pose a greater short-term threat to governmentstability than do communist rebels, who have fought to topple thegovernment for nearly 20 years.   After 20 years as president, Marcos was forced into exile by amilitary-civilian uprising in February 1986 and he was replaced byMrs. Aquino.</TEXT></DOC>